{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure boundary is real filesystem watcher behavior (recursive/child path event delivery), which is OS- and watcher-implementation-dependent. A mocked event source can hide real missed-subdirectory events.","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temp directory tree, create a nested subdirectory under the watched root, write a file inside it, and assert the transformed output appears in the output directory. Use real filesystem operations and real watcher subscription lifecycle.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.84,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is primarily cross-module state handoff (ingress request -> dedupe store/window logic -> pipeline trigger). It does not require real OS/network/subprocess to expose the core failure; an in-process wired test with controllable time catches real regressions.","test_description":"Wire the request-ingest path, dedupe component, and processing trigger together in-process. Submit two requests for the same path within the configured window and assert only one processing execution occurs; then submit after window expiry and assert processing occurs again.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Rejected System because behavior text targets duplicate processing requests and windowed suppression logic, not OS-specific watcher/event semantics." ,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The behavior explicitly depends on OS-emitted duplicate filesystem events. Mocking event emission can trivially pass while missing real duplicate-event patterns from actual watchers.","test_description":"Run daemon with a real watched directory, perform a write pattern known to trigger multiple events (e.g., write+rename or editor-style temp-file swap), and assert exactly one processing/output artifact for that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.93,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a real OS filesystem lifecycle condition (directory deletion/recreation invalidating watcher handles). In-process fakes often miss watcher teardown/rebind edge cases.","test_description":"Launch daemon watching a real directory, remove that directory, recreate it at the same path, then add a new file and assert it is processed without restarting the daemon.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.94,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Correctness depends on interaction between watcher event bursts and real filesystem timestamp metadata/precision. Mocked timestamps/events can hide ordering failures that only appear with real FS semantics.","test_description":"Create multiple files in rapid succession in the real watched directory (including near-identical timestamps), capture processing order from daemon outputs/logs, and assert ordering matches creation timestamps with defined tie-breaking behavior.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a real I/O race between file writes and watcher-triggered processing. The failure appears under actual filesystem buffering/flush/lock timing; mocks usually cannot reproduce it faithfully.","test_description":"Open a file in the watched directory, write it in chunks with delays while keeping the handle open, trigger watcher visibility, and assert processing does not start until the writer closes (or stability criteria is met), then verify exactly one successful processed output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.84,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
